
# 📄 UI Implementation Document – Candidate Pipeline

---

## 1. Overview

This document defines how the Candidate Pipeline will be implemented at the UI level.

The UI is designed to:

* Clearly separate **candidate evaluation (ATS)** from **hiring execution (Pipeline)**
* Provide a simple and fast decision-making experience for HR and TA
* Avoid unnecessary technical complexity in the interface
* Handle large candidate datasets efficiently

---

## 2. Navigation Structure

The application will have a sidebar-based navigation system with the following sections:

* Dashboard
* Requisitions
* Candidates (Global)


All candidate pipeline actions will be performed inside the **Requisition Detail Page**.

---

## 3. Requisition List Page

The Requisition List page displays all requisitions in the system.

Each row includes:

* Requisition ID
* Job Title
* Status (Pending, Approved, Closed)
* Assigned TA

Available actions:

* View Requisition
* Edit Requisition
* Assign TA

Selecting a requisition opens the **Requisition Detail Page**.

---

## 4. Requisition Detail Page

This is the primary working screen for the candidate pipeline.

The page is divided into three main tabs:

* ATS View
* Shortlisted
* Interviews

Each tab represents a different stage of the pipeline.

---

## 5. ATS View (Evaluation Layer)

The ATS View is used for evaluating candidates.

Only candidates who have applied to the selected requisition are shown.

The layout is a Kanban-style board with five buckets:

* BEST
* VERY GOOD
* GOOD
* AVERAGE
* NOT SUITABLE

Each bucket contains candidate cards grouped by their evaluation score.

---

### Candidate Card (ATS View)

Each candidate card displays:

* Candidate Name
* Final Score (optional label like “Very Good”)
* Key highlights (skills, experience)
* 1–2 risk indicators (missing skills, gaps)

Available actions:

* Shortlist
* View Details

---

### Rules for ATS View

* No interview-related actions are allowed
* No stage movement is allowed
* Only evaluation and shortlisting actions are permitted
* Data is always fetched from the applications table

---

## 6. Candidate Detail View

When a user clicks “View” on a candidate, a detail panel or page opens.

This includes:

* Basic information (name, email, phone)
* Skills and experience
* Resume preview or download
* AI summary (if available)
* Score breakdown (simplified, not raw technical values)

This view is read-only for evaluation purposes.

---

## 7. Shortlisted Tab (Execution Layer)

The Shortlisted tab contains candidates who have been shortlisted.

Only candidates with stage = SHORTLISTED are shown.

---

### Layout

A simple list or table of shortlisted candidates is displayed.

Each row includes:

* Candidate Name
* Experience summary
* Status

---

### Available Actions

* Schedule Interview
* Reject Candidate
* Move to next stage

---

### Rules

* ATS scores are not emphasized here
* The focus is on actions, not evaluation
* All actions are applied at the application level

---

## 8. Interview Tab

The Interview tab is used to manage scheduled interviews.

---

### Layout

A table-based view showing:

* Candidate Name
* Interview Date
* Interview Type
* Status (Scheduled, Completed, Cancelled)

---

### Available Actions

* Schedule Interview
* Reschedule Interview
* Add Feedback
* Move candidate to next stage

---

---

## 9. Bulk Actions (Shortlisted Only)

Bulk actions are available only in the Shortlisted section.

These include:

* Sending bulk emails
* Moving multiple candidates to the next stage

Users can select multiple candidates and apply actions at once.

---

## 10. Global Candidates Page

This page displays all candidates stored in the system.

Each row includes:

* Candidate Name
* Source (LinkedIn, Career Page, Manual, etc.)
* Number of applications

Available actions:

* View candidate profile
* Apply candidate to a requisition

---

## 11. UI Data Flow

The UI must always follow this data flow:

* Candidates are fetched via applications
* ATS View uses applications filtered by requisition
* Shortlisted View uses applications filtered by stage
* No direct dependency on the global candidates table for pipeline views

---

## 12. User Interaction Flow

The expected user flow is:

1. User opens a requisition
2. ATS View loads candidates grouped by buckets
3. User evaluates candidates
4. User shortlists selected candidates
5. User switches to Shortlisted tab
6. User schedules interviews
7. User manages interview process
8. Candidate moves to final outcome (Hired or Rejected)

---

## 13. UI Constraints and Guidelines

* The interface must remain simple and readable
* Candidate cards should not display excessive data
* No raw technical scoring fields should be shown
* All scoring should be translated into human-readable insights
* ATS and Pipeline views must remain clearly separated

---

## 14. Summary

The UI is divided into two primary layers:

1. Evaluation Layer (ATS View)

   * Used to compare and shortlist candidates
   * Based on ranking and bucket classification

2. Execution Layer (Shortlisted + Interview Tabs)

   * Used to perform hiring actions
   * Focused on scheduling, communication, and decisions

